The recommender system made unsuitable recommendation. 
 Its reasons are as follows: Extraction of my stated preferences and dislikes:
- Preferences: well‑curated greatest‑hits pop compilations with radio‑length singles and singalong choruses; tight sequencing; warm, restrained remastering that still yields elastic low end, natural drum tone, crisp (not over‑glossy) stereo imaging, and punchy, dynamic mastering; melody‑forward, instrument‑forward pop that preserves vocal clarity and intimate harmony work. I also still value cleanly remastered releases with clarity and punch, emotive lead vocals front‑and‑center, and concise radio arrangements.
- Dislikes: groove‑first, album‑style dance records that bury vocal nuance; arena‑scale stadium rock that buries vocal detail; midrange‑heavy MOR/sleepy balladry; loose, under‑remastered vintage blues lacking stereo focus.
Evaluation and decision:
Journey: Greatest Hits aligns strongly with my current priorities. It is explicitly a greatest‑hits compilation of concise, hook‑driven 3–5‑minute singles and is sequenced for radio‑forward immediacy — exactly the “well‑curated greatest‑hits” format I favor. The listed mastering — punchy, controlled with tight bass/drums, bright synths and layered guitars, dry front‑and‑center lead vocals and lush multi‑part harmonies — checks many boxes: elastic low end and natural drum tone, vocal clarity, and punchy yet tasteful compression that preserves transients. Those attributes reward repeat listening and emphasize singalong choruses and front‑to‑back playability in the way I described.
Best of Simon & Garfunkel, while excellent for my earlier tastes (sensitive fingerpicked arrangements, richly blended vocal harmonies, warm analogue tonality, spacious imaging and preserved headroom), is a different flavor: intimate, guitar‑centric, and dynamic in a subdued, live‑in‑the‑room way. That very intimacy is why I enjoy it historically, but it less directly satisfies my current emphasis on greatest‑hits, radio‑length pop sequencing and punchy, radio‑ready mastering with an elastic low end and forward drum presence. In short, Simon & Garfunkel delivers superb acoustic warmth and harmony detail but not the hook‑driven, punchy pop compilation experience I’m prioritizing now.
