 Its reasons are as follows: 1) Extracted preferences and dislikes (from my self‑introduction)
- Preferences: polished but transparently low‑compression transfers; guitar‑forward arrangements with warm tape midrange; close, front‑of‑mix lead vocals and tight multi‑part harmonies; snappy, natural drums; wide yet focused stereo imaging that preserves headroom and microdetail; intimate, close‑miked presence and LP‑style pacing; snappy, realistic transients; warm analogue tone and honest spatial cues.
- Dislikes: heavy mastering compression/limiting or brickwall loudness; gated/artificial drum sounds; dense mixes that bury guitars and harmonies; thin/cluttered mixes or ragged, unfocused lead takes; uneven sequencing/mastering.
2) Evaluation of the two candidates against those criteria
- Elton John — One Night Only (live at MSG): Pros relative to my list: piano‑front and close‑miked tactile piano give strong front‑of‑mix presence; breathy, charismatic lead vocal provides immediacy; drums are described as natural and minimally compressed, and dynamics/theatrical pacing are preserved — all positive regarding low compression, natural transients and live spatial cues. Cons relative to my list: it is piano‑front and performance‑driven rather than guitar‑forward; being a live, theatrical record it will emphasize stage immediacy and crowd/room ambience over the intimate, LP‑style sequencing and tight studio‑style vocal/guitar interplay I prize. The description does not emphasize stacked harmonies, warm tape midrange for guitars, or the concise, guitar‑led arrangements I prefer.
- Careful remaster (intimate vocal–guitar folk): This explicitly hits a long list of my priorities: close‑miked vocal–guitar interplay, generous headroom, warm tape sheen, preserved microdynamics, midrange‑centered lead vocals up front, minimal overdubs, LP‑style sequencing, natural room cues and restrained mastering. Those attributes map directly to my stated tastes: guitar‑forward clarity, analogue warmth, preserved transients and headroom, intimate presentation, and avoidance of heavy limiting/compression and dense mixes.
3) Reason for choosing the remaster and rejecting the Elton live album
- Why I chose the careful remaster: It aligns more comprehensively with the core details of my preferences. I explicitly prize intimate, guitar‑led clarity, close‑miked presence, warm tape midrange and LP‑style pacing; the remaster states all of those characteristics. The generous headroom and preserved microdynamics speak directly to my dislike of heavy mastering compression and my desire for natural transients and microdetail. Midrange‑centered lead vocals and minimal overdubs will keep the vocal and guitar up front and uncluttered — exactly the sort of tactile, conversational analogue sound that best fits my listening priorities.
- Why I rejected Elton — One Night Only: While the live Elton disc has many virtues (minimal compression on drums, tactile piano, preserved dynamics and immediate, charismatic vocals), it misses the primary things I emphasized: it is piano‑front and performance/theatre driven rather than guitar‑forward and tightly arranged around vocal–guitar interplay. I value tight stacked harmonies, concise LP‑style sequencing and a warm tape midrange for guitar as a core preference; those specific features are made explicit in the remaster, but not in the Elton live description. Furthermore, a live theatrical pacing — even when well‑recorded — can work against the intimate, studio‑like conversations between voice and guitar that give me the particular enjoyment I described.
In short: both CDs avoid the worst of heavy compression and offer preserved dynamics, but the careful remaster matches a greater number of my specific, stated preferences (guitar‑forward warmth, close‑miked vocals, LP pacing, preserved microdynamics), so it is the better fit for my taste.

